run program with

python main.py

Big picture
Parser — Define how to read fields from a PDF → saved under flowdesk\rules\ as JSON.
Targets — Save small screenshots of buttons/fields QuickBooks (or any app) shows on screen → flowdesk\targets\.
Automations — Define steps (hotkeys, type text, click/wait on targets) → flowdesk\automations\.
Runner — Pick PDF + rule set + automation, then run: for each row the parser returns, it runs all automation steps and fills {{field_name}} from that row.
1. Parser tab — extraction rules
Rule sets — Left: create a set with New Set (stored as rules\<name>.json).

Rules — Each rule has:

Rule name — becomes the variable name, e.g. customer_name → use {{customer_name}} in automations.
Anchor — text to find (can match a single word or a short phrase the parser joins).
Direction — right = Nth word to the right on the same line; below = Nth word below in the same column.
Offset — which word (1 = first after the anchor).
Load PDF + Run Rules — Tests on a sample PDF; results show in the table (one row per “record” the parser finds).

Multi-row PDFs: The engine splits “records” by repeating the first rule’s anchor on the page. Design that first rule so its anchor appears once per logical record (e.g. per invoice).

2. Targets tab — screen images
Capture New Target — Window minimizes; drag a rectangle on screen; name the file (saved as targets\<name>.png).
Adjust confidence per image if matching is flaky; values are stored in targets\meta.json.
PyAutoGUI failsafe: moving the mouse to a screen corner aborts automation (built into the library).
3. Automations tab — what to automate
Pick or create an automation (JSON under automations\).

Steps — Add steps; reorder by dragging or Move Up / Down.

For each step type:

click_image / wait_for_image — Choose a PNG from targets\, set confidence if needed.
type_value — Literal text or placeholders like {{customer_name}}.
hotkey — Comma-separated keys, e.g. ctrl,f or ctrl,shift,s.
loop_over_list — In the UI it’s tied to a field name; the runner already loops once per parsed record, so this step is effectively a marker (the executor treats it as a no-op “ok” step).
On Error — Choose behavior when a step fails (e.g. abort vs skip record), per your automation JSON.

4. Runner tab — run end-to-end
Automation — Which JSON workflow to run.
Rule set — Same rules you used to design/test the PDF.
Load PDF — The file to process (often the same type you tested in Parser).
Loop delay — Seconds between records (default 3s); gives the desktop app time to finish dialogs.
Run — Parses the PDF, then for each record runs every step with {{...}} filled from that record.
Pause / Stop — Pause freezes between steps; Stop ends the run.

Emergency stop: Ctrl+Shift+Q stops the runner if it’s running.

Logs appear in the window and are also written under flowdesk\logs\ with a timestamp in the filename.

Tips
Build rules and targets on real samples first; use Parser → Run Rules until the table looks right.
Keep target images small and unique (one button, one field) for reliable locateOnScreen.
Runner needs the target app visible (e.g. QuickBooks) in a consistent layout where your PNGs still match.
loop_over_list vs looping
The runner’s outer loop is: for each parsed record → run all steps. You do not need a special step to “start the loop.” The loop_over_list action is present in the UI for documentation/field selection; execution still follows the “one full pass per record” model above.
